#compdef lucky
# ============================================================================
# lucky - Multipurpose home-router network tool (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : gdy666
# Upstream: https://github.com/gdy666/lucky
#
# Lucky ("软硬路由公网神器" - "soft+hard router public-network
# wonder-tool") is the Chinese-language Go-ecosystem swiss-army
# knife for hobbyist home-router operators. Ships as a single
# binary that serves a web admin UI on a configurable port and
# wraps a bundle of network features into one process:
#
#   - IPv6/IPv4 port forwarding (TCP+UDP relay rules)
#   - HTTP/HTTPS reverse proxy + SNI-based routing
#   - DDNS clients for dozens of providers (Cloudflare, DNSPod,
#     Aliyun, Tencent, Namecheap, Namesilo, Godaddy, ...)
#   - WOL (Wake-on-LAN) on demand and on schedule
#   - IPv4 STUN-based intranet penetration (NAT traversal for
#     IPv4-only ISPs)
#   - cron-style scheduled task runner
#   - ACME (Let's Encrypt) certificate issuance + renewal
#   - rclone integration for cloud-storage sync
#   - built-in FTP server
#   - built-in WebDAV server
#   - MQTT client for IoT-style event publishing
#
# All features are configured + monitored through the single
# web admin UI (default localhost:16601). The CLI itself is
# tiny - it just bootstraps the web server with the chosen
# config file.
#
# Flags (Go stdlib `flag`):
#   -p <port>     - http admin web listen port (default 16601)
#   -c <url>      - configure file URL (local path or HTTP URL)
#
# The paho.mqtt.golang lane is built on `github.com/eclipse/
# paho.mqtt.golang v1.4.1` (declared verbatim at upstream
# go.mod HEAD), the canonical Go MQTT 3.1.1 client maintained
# by the Eclipse Foundation (github.com/eclipse-paho/
# paho.mqtt.golang, 2900+ stars). Eclipse Paho is *the* MQTT
# reference-implementation umbrella - the project ships
# clients in C / C++ / Java / Python / JavaScript / Go / .NET
# / Embedded-C, all in the same monorepo-of-repos structure.
# The Go client is the de-facto choice for any Go program
# that needs to publish or subscribe MQTT topics. lucky uses
# it for the MQTT-event publishing feature (DDNS update
# notifications, port-forwarding rule changes, WOL execution
# logs) and for MQTT-trigger automations (subscribe to a
# topic, run a relay rule or WOL when a payload arrives).
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 227 :: MQTT clients (IoT pub/sub messaging protocol)
# Round 1380 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 227
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : bytebeamio/rumqtt            [R1379 _edgelinkd]
#   Go      : eclipse-paho/paho.mqtt.golang [R1380 THIS FILE]
#   TS/Node : mqttjs/MQTT.js               [R1381 closing]
#
# paho.mqtt.golang is structurally interesting in this axis:
# it is one of very few cases where the *MQTT spec authors*
# (Eclipse Paho, OASIS-affiliated) maintain the canonical
# implementation per language. This is the same pattern seen
# in Axis 207 (panva/oauth4webapi - same maintainer as the
# OAuth/JWT/JOSE specs in node-oidc-provider) and Axis 216
# (vscode-languageserver-node - LSP spec maintained by
# Microsoft, who also maintain the reference Node impl).
# Spec-author-as-library-maintainer guarantees byte-for-byte
# spec compliance across versions.
#
# The cross-language interop story for MQTT is total: an
# MQTT 5 PUBLISH packet emitted by rumqttc (Rust),
# paho.mqtt.golang (Go), or MQTT.js (Node) is received
# identically by any of the others (or by Mosquitto / EMQX /
# HiveMQ / VerneMQ brokers). The wire format is small enough
# (~4KB spec PDF) that misimplementation is rare.
# ============================================================================

_lucky() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '-p[http Admin Web listen port (default 16601)]:port:' \
        '-c[configure file URL (path or HTTP URL)]:url:_files' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]'
}

_lucky "$@"
